Part 1: Data

A brief introduction to the General Social Survey (GSS):

  • Gathers data on contemporary American society (since 1972) to monitor and explain trends in social attitudes, behaviors, and attributes.
  • Among topics of interest surveyed are opinions regarding civil liberties, crime and violence, intergroup tolerance, morality, and psychological well-being.
  • Allows researchers and any interested parties to study the structure and functioning of the American society and its many sub-groups over time, and to compare findings to that of other nations.

Data collection methods:

1. Generalizability: Random sampling methods were used on a household and individual level.

  • A single household’s address will be randomly selected to represent a cross section of the country - a selected household will essentially be representing 50,000 other households of the same cross section.
  • All households across the country have an equal chance of being selected for the survey.
  • Subsequently, an adult member from each of the selected household will be randomly selected to complete the interview.
  • From the above given information, it looks like the survey methodology utilises a stratified sampling method in which the population as a whole is divided into separate groups, called strata, then a simple random sample is drawn from each group where in this context, households representing 50,000 other households are randomly selected.
  • Thus, based simply on the sampling method mentioned, it is fair to conclude (theoretically) that results of the survey are generalizable to the entire US population.

2. Bias:

  • However, biases may be present where in actual fact, results may not be representative of the total population. Such biases may include non-response bias or other forms of selection bias. Response biases may also occur where questions are not answered accurately and truthfully.

3. Correlation does not mean causation:

  • Since the GSS is an observational study, results can only be assessed for association, and not causality. This is unlike an experimental study where the random assignment of control and intervention groups will take place.

Part 2: Research question

Does the American population view certain government obligations and responsibilities differently based on their political party affiliation?

I wish to explore the above question in light of the current political climate in the US where it seems to me that divisions of views regarding various national social concerns are becoming increasingly wide among the American population, especially between Democrats and Republicans. Such social concerns include views on abortion, gun possession, and homosexuality, as well as opinions on how the government should best utilise funds for the alleviation of certain issues (or not). My research question focuses on the last subject.

Part 3: Exploratory data analysis

This exercise uses the following variables:

1. “PARTYID”

  • Political party affiliation as the explanatory variable
  • Categorical variable
  • Survey question: Generally speaking, do you usually think of yourself as a Republican, Democrat, Independent, or what?

2. “HELPPOOR”

  • Views on whether or not the government should improve the standard of living of all poor Americans as response variable #1
  • Categorical variable
  • Survey question: Some people think that the government in Washington should do everything possible to improve the standard of living of all poor Americans; they are at point 1 on this card. Other people think itis not the government’s responsibility, and that each person should take care of himself; they are at point 5. a. Where would you place yourself on this scale, or haven’t you made up your mind on this?

3. “HELPBLK”

  • views on whether or not the government should be giving special treatment to African-Americans as response variable #2
  • Categorical variable
  • Survey question: Some people think that (blacks/negroes/African-Americans) have been discriminated against for so long that the government has a special obligation to help improve their living standards; they are at point 1. Others believe that the government should not be giving special treatment to (blacks/negroes/African-Americans); they are at point 5. a. Where would you place yourself on this scale, or haven’t you made up your mind on this?

Next, I produce simple summary statistics and graphs to display the distribution of sample observations of my variables of interest according to political party affiliation.

I will also plot time-graphs to explore the distribution of observations over time (without grouping them into political party affiliation). I thought it’d be interesting to see if there are changes in people’s views over time. However, since I am only plotting frequencies/ counts, as opposed to proportions, the time-graphs are not as meaningful as they can be. This is because any observed fluctuations may be attributable to changes in the total number of survey participants.

As such, I will be presenting three sets of results:

  • Table of summary statistics
  • Boxplot displaying distribution of sample observations according to political party affiliation
  • Time-graph

Limitations of MY summary statistics and graphs: Across these visualisations, only obviously large patterns of differences between variables may I confidently note. These graphs also do not show me if differences observed are statistically significant.

Part 4: Inference

I will be using a chi-square test for a two-way table to evaluate if my explanatory and response variables are independent from one another - if political party affiliation and views on government obligations and responsibilities (regarding two issues) are independent. If differences between the distribution of variables are statistically significant (<0.05), then there is a high likelihood that the observed relationship is caused by something other than chance - suggesting variables dependency.

1) Should the government improve standard of living of all poor Americans?

Set out hypotheses

Null hypothesis: There is no difference in views between people of different political party affiliation on whether or not the government should do everything possible to improve the standard of living of all poor Americans.

Alternate hypothesis: There is some difference in views.

Check conditions

  • Independence: Independence condition met - random sampling method is used.
  • Sample size/ skew: Number of sample observation in each level is more than 5.

Perform inference

#create dataframe
partyid_helppoor<-as.data.frame.matrix(table(gss$PARTYID,gss$HELPPOOR))%>%rename("govt action"=1,"agree both"=3,"ppl help selves"=5)

#inference test 1
chisq_results1<-chisq.test(partyid_helppoor)
print(chisq_results1)
## 
##  Pearson's Chi-squared test
## 
## data:  partyid_helppoor
## X-squared = 3595.4, df = 28, p-value < 2.2e-16
#work behind the chi-square test
chisq_results1$observed #calculate observed counts for each level
##                    govt action   2 agree both    4 ppl help selves
## STRONG DEMOCRAT           1601 872       1977  278             352
## NOT STR DEMOCRAT          1172 992       2956  658             466
## IND,NEAR DEM               725 683       1872  381             260
## INDEPENDENT                904 505       2304  504             476
## IND,NEAR REP               280 323       1266  634             457
## NOT STR REPUBLICAN         442 467       2244 1180             685
## STRONG REPUBLICAN          236 180       1171  824             786
## OTHER PARTY                 82  57        197   90              85
chisq_results1$expected #calculate expected counts for each level 
##                    govt action         2 agree both         4 ppl help selves
## STRONG DEMOCRAT      874.18922 655.24032  2246.8366 730.73994       572.99393
## NOT STR DEMOCRAT    1074.49557 805.37807  2761.6629 898.17721       704.28624
## IND,NEAR DEM         674.74330 505.74750  1734.2217 564.02191       442.26559
## INDEPENDENT          807.59252 605.32339  2075.6701 675.07137       529.34262
## IND,NEAR REP         509.37010 381.79357  1309.1804 425.78548       333.87048
## NOT STR REPUBLICAN   863.51998 647.24330  2219.4146 721.82146       566.00070
## STRONG REPUBLICAN    550.15412 412.36286  1414.0033 459.87709       360.60268
## OTHER PARTY           87.93518  65.91099   226.0105  73.50553        57.63778

Interpret results

The chi-square test statistic produced is 3556.6 with a degrees of freedom of 28. Because we would typically test at a significance level of alpha=0.05, and the p-value is less than 0.05, I will reject the null hypothesis. That is, the data provide convincing evidence that there is some difference in views between people of different political party affiliation on whether or not the government should do everything possible to improve the standard of living of all poor Americans.

Additional: Studying the nature of dependence between the various levels of the variables

I want to know which cell/ level is contributing most to the total chi-square score. I calculate Pearson residuals (r) for this.

  • Positive residuals are in blue. These values imply that a positive association exist between the corresponding row and column variables.
  • Negative residuals are in red. These values imply that a negative association exist between the corresponding variables.
#download package
library(corrplot)
